Sarah Shapiro
Sarah Shapiro

* Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s bye-bye to
San Francisco: News of the closure of the San Francisco Bloomingdale=E2=80=
=99s, announced Tuesday, was more disappointing than surprising. When I wor=
ked at the company, I helped develop those original floor plans, and still =
recall the team=E2=80=99s excitement about expanding in NorCal beyond the P=
alo Alto location. The iconic black and white Bway, as the deco floor tile =
is known at the company, reminded me of my old life back in Manhattan.

Objectively, though, in the two decades the store
was open, it never achieved strong product-market fit. The Bay Area custome=
r has a=E2=80=A6 unique style, and this location never quite adapted to the=
 local shopper. Alas, I=E2=80=99ve heard from inside the company that the s=
tore had been struggling for a while, and the Palo Alto location always per=
formed better. In 2014, they=E2=80=99d revamped that location and moved to =
a smaller space, allowing for a more edited assortment better geared to the=
 local customer.=C2=A0

Meanwhile, Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s is
enjoying more success these days with their smaller =E2=80=9CBloomie=E2=80=
=99s=E2=80=9D format shops=E2=80=94their new Shrewsbury, New Jersey, locati=
on reportedly had their strongest opening yet. There are currently only fou=
r Bloomie=E2=80=99s, but many more markets can successfully support a 20,00=
0-square-foot store versus a larger department store. (San Francisco is mor=
e than 300,000 square feet.) Could a smaller-footprint Bloomie=E2=80=99s be=
tter serve the S.F. market? After all, the focused merchandising and reduce=
d inventory overhead
would better align with the local consumer=E2=80=99s needs, and allow the m=
erchants to buy only products that will actually sell. Plus, while downtown=
 S.F. has become overridden with urban blight=E2=80=94persistent homelessne=
ss tends to be a drag for retail consumption=E2=80=94off-center areas like =
Fillmore Street and Hayes Valley are faring better with smaller, more focus=
ed boutiques.

Of course, the broader challenge for San Francisco retail extends beyond Bl=
oomingdale=E2=80=99s: The apocalyptic streetscape surrounding
Union Square has created a domino effect on all retailers. And the departur=
e of another anchor will continue to pull down the entire ecosystem. The cu=
rrent Union Square tally sheet looks like this: Nordstrom is gone, Macy=E2=
=80=99s is closing, Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s will leave this spring, Saks is =
appointment-only and looking grim, and Barney=E2=80=99s has been R.I.P. for=
 a while even though the sign still tragically hangs out front. Neiman Marc=
us: Don=E2=80=99t leave!

* Will
LVMH consider spinning off its booze division?: Bernstein superstar analyst=
 Luca Solca made a compelling argument this week. While it=E2=80=99s easy t=
o think of 75-maison-strong LVMH as incredibly diversified=E2=80=94with bus=
iness interests in luxury fashion, media, hospitality, beauty, fine jewelry=
, and wine and spirits, among other sectors=E2=80=94the business disproport=
ionately =E2=80=9Chinges,=E2=80=9D as Luca recently put it, on fashion and =
leather goods, a topic we grazed over on a
fairlyrecent episode ( https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/fashions-fake-=
ish-crisis/id1741589082?i=3D1000673961058&utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%281%2F22%2F25%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F21%2=
F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c606=
17da42abd12a ) of Fashion People.

For many years, this wasn=E2=80=99t the case: Even 15 years ago, LVMH was m=
ore or less as reliant on fashion and leather goods for profits and return =
on invested capital as it was on wine and spirits. Now, though, fashion and=
 leather goods generate more than 10x the profits of wine and spirits,
and the share price depends on the performance of the former category more =
than anything else.=C2=A0

In a recent note, Luca argued that the wine and spirits category simply doe=
sn=E2=80=99t fit with LVMH=E2=80=99s current strategy. First off, it=E2=80=
=99s a wholesale business=E2=80=94LVMH cannot control distribution, or even=
 all brand communication, because of the way alcohol is bought and sold. Al=
so, a lot of funds and asset managers=E2=80=94in the Middle East and beyond=
=E2=80=94will not invest in LVMH because of the spirits business.
(Pesky E.S.G. principles=E2=80=A6) =E2=80=9CThis blemish contributes to pre=
venting LVMH from reaching =E2=80=98absolute blue chip=E2=80=99 status,=E2=
=80=9D next to L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al, Herm=C3=A8s, or Ferrari, Luca declared=
=2E=C2=A0

So what=E2=80=99s the solution? Well, LVMH could consider selling to partne=
r Diageo, which already owns a 34 percent stake in the business, but LVMH d=
oesn=E2=80=99t need the cash. LVMH could also restructure as Richemont once=
 did, back in 2008, when the company created a special purpose vehicle, cal=
led Reinet, for its tobacco
businesses. In this scenario, LVMH could subsequently distribute shares of =
the S.P.V. to their shareholders. Unfortunately, a =E2=80=9Cplain vanilla s=
plit,=E2=80=9D as Luca called it, would put the Arnault family at risk of l=
osing control, so they=E2=80=99ll have to figure out a different way.=C2=A0

Hennessy=E2=80=94the rare bird with the category expertise and financial ch=
ops, according to Luca, to solve this riddle. Alexandre Arnault, Mo=C3=ABt =
Hennessy=E2=80=99s incoming deputy C.E.O.,
would benefit, too, if they were able to pull it off. =E2=80=9CThis could b=
e an opportunity for Alexandre=E2=80=A6 to burnish his personal brand in M&=
A,=E2=80=9D Luca wrote, =E2=80=9Cas it seems fitting for an aspiring succes=
sor to the =E2=80=98wolf in cashmere.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Guiony and Arnault =
officially start their new roles on February 1.
* Solving another Jonathan mystery: While the consensus is that Jonathan An=
derson is headed for Dior to design both menswear
and womenswear=E2=80=94a feat, if true=E2=80=94you may wonder what that mea=
ns for his namesake collection, J.W. Anderson. Last year, as you may recall=
, I reported that J.W.A. would need to be sold in order to clear the runway=
 for its founder to accept a big job at another group. Running both women=
=E2=80=99s and men=E2=80=99s at Dior and at J.W.A. sounded virtually imposs=
ible, even for Anderson.

Anyway, I=E2=80=99ve since learned that Anderson is prioritizing J.W.A. as =
he ostensibly heads out the door. The
brand is ramping up on distribution at the moment, and the business is grow=
ing. Sorry to be vague here, but I need to protect my sources. You=E2=80=99=
ll be the first to know when there=E2=80=99s more I can share=E2=80=A6

