om:0;list-style-type:revert;"><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Blooming=
dale=E2=80=99s bye-bye to
San Francisco</em>: News of the closure of the San Francisco Bloomingdale=
=E2=80=99s, announced Tuesday, was more disappointing than surprising. When=
 I worked at the company, I helped develop those original floor plans, and =
still recall the team=E2=80=99s excitement about expanding in NorCal beyond=
 the Palo Alto location. The iconic black and white <em>Bway</em>, as the d=
eco floor tile is known at the company, reminded me of my old life back in =
Manhattan.<br/><br/>Objectively, though, in the two decades the store
was open, it never achieved strong product-market fit. The Bay Area custome=
r has a=E2=80=A6 <em>unique</em> style, and this location never quite adapt=
ed to the local shopper. Alas, I=E2=80=99ve heard from inside the company t=
hat the store had been struggling for a while, and the Palo Alto location a=
lways performed better. In 2014, they=E2=80=99d revamped that location and =
moved to a smaller space, allowing for a more edited assortment better gear=
ed to the local customer.=C2=A0<br/><br/>Meanwhile, Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s =
is
enjoying more success these days with their smaller =E2=80=9CBloomie=E2=80=
=99s=E2=80=9D format shops=E2=80=94their new Shrewsbury, New Jersey, locati=
on reportedly had their strongest opening yet. There are currently only fou=
r Bloomie=E2=80=99s, but many more markets can successfully support a 20,00=
0-square-foot store versus a larger department store. (San Francisco is mor=
e than 300,000 square feet.) Could a smaller-footprint Bloomie=E2=80=99s be=
tter serve the S.F. market? After all, the focused merchandising and reduce=
d inventory overhead
would better align with the local consumer=E2=80=99s needs, and allow the m=
erchants to buy only products that will actually sell. Plus, while downtown=
 S.F. has become overridden with urban blight=E2=80=94persistent homelessne=
ss tends to be a drag for retail consumption=E2=80=94off-center areas like =
Fillmore Street and Hayes Valley are faring better with smaller, more focus=
ed boutiques.<br/><br/>Of course, the broader challenge for San Francisco r=
etail extends beyond Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s: The apocalyptic streetscape su=
rrounding
Union Square has created a domino effect on <em>all</em> retailers. And the=
 departure of another anchor will continue to pull down the entire ecosyste=
m. The current Union Square tally sheet looks like this: Nordstrom is gone,=
 Macy=E2=80=99s is closing, Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s will leave this spring, =
Saks is appointment-only and looking grim, and Barney=E2=80=99s has been R.=
I.P. for a while even though the sign still tragically hangs out front. Nei=
man Marcus: <em>Don=E2=80=99t leave</em>!</li></ul></div>
