ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Earlier this week, I heard from a source that <strong>Simone</strong>
<strong>Bellotti</strong>, the creative director of Bally, had a new job=E2=
=80=94and that this mysterious new job was in Milan. The consensus among pe=
ople on the circumference of the situation was that he was going to Jil San=
der, owned by <strong>Renzo</strong> <strong>Rosso</strong>=E2=80=99s OTB a=
nd designed by the husband-and-wife team of <strong>Luke</strong> and <stro=
ng>Lucie</strong> <strong>Meier</strong>, who did not seem long for the rol=
e. Within a day, <em>WWD </em>released a story saying as much.</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">A rep for OTB did not have any comment regarding what I an=
d others have learned. Bally was more forthcoming, stating that Bellotti wi=
ll show a co-ed collection on March 1. =E2=80=9CBuilding on the success of =
past editions, we are committed to making [Bally] once again a defining tri=
bute to Swiss heritage,=E2=80=9D the statement read.<br/><br/>Sounds like B=
ellotti is wrapping things up at Bally before moving on. But the news
got me thinking about Bellotti=E2=80=99s own amazing, and surprising, ascen=
t. Few noticed, in May 2023, when the 14-year Gucci veteran was promoted to=
 become creative director of Bally, the Swiss leather goods house best know=
n for its men=E2=80=99s shoes and that brief period during the 1980s when i=
ts designer sneakers were beloved by hip-hop artists. Bellotti=E2=80=99s pr=
edecessor, <strong>Rhuigi</strong> <strong>Villase=C3=B1or</strong>, was a =
merch king from the San Fernando Valley who came in hot with ill-conceived
riffs on <strong>Tom</strong> <strong>Ford</strong>=E2=80=93era Gucci, and =
my assumption was that its then-owners, JAB=E2=80=94the <strong>Reimann</st=
rong> family=E2=80=99s conglomerate, which owns everything from Krispy Krem=
e to Panera Bread=E2=80=94would finally give up on the line.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">After all, the Reimanns made a real play at luxury about a deca=
de ago, acquiring Jimmy Choo, Belstaff, and Bally, only to announce they we=
re getting
out almost as quickly as they got in. While they shed Jimmy Choo and Belsta=
ff fairly quickly, nobody wanted Bally, and the Villase=C3=B1or play felt l=
ike a last-ditch attempt to capitalize on the already near-dead branded-hig=
h-fashion trend.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Most of us went to Bellotti=E2=
=80=99s first show, in the summer of 2023, out of respect for the involved =
P.R.s, but were rewarded with a genuine moment of delight. Bellotti
was <em>good</em>: His clothes and bags were at once commercial<em> and</em=
> inventive. His designs, assisted by the masterful styling of <strong>Char=
lotte</strong> <strong>Collet</strong>, were both preppy and depraved. They=
 featured Swiss cowbell=E2=80=93inspired hems, which hung on the very good =
handbags and dangled from the edges of boat shoes, plus V-shaped waists, of=
ten rendered in schoolboy colors of navy, red, and yellow, and topped with =
sinister black leather. Editors filled up with hope.
Influencers bought boat shoes.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">By the time Bellot=
ti presented his third collection in the cloister of San Simpliciano Basili=
ca, last September in Milan, the momentum was <em>real</em>. Net-a-Porter p=
icked it up and the shoes sold out. Meanwhile, the Reimanns were gone. The =
summer before, Bally had been acquired by Regent, the Los Angeles=E2=80=93b=
ased private equity firm that owns a whole host of fashion and
retail brands, including Club Monaco, Intermix, Escada, and Sassoon, but al=
so Drybar, <em>Sunset</em> magazine, and Cheddar. (Like many other P.E. fir=
ms, Regent is known for stripping out costs from the companies it acquires =
and harvesting the short-term profits.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I wondered, the=
n, what Regent founder <strong>Michael A.</strong> <strong>Reinstein</stron=
g> planned to do with Bally. Sure, the fervor was
limited to a subset of fashion consumers, but it was also undeniable. (Thes=
e days, success in fashion is often measured by the<em> sell-through</em> r=
ate, not the overall number of units sold. Bally was selling out the little=
 inventory it had on several popular styles=E2=80=94and not just the boat s=
hoes.) Reinstein made an appearance at the Milan show, accompanied by a wed=
ding-ring-free <strong>Cheryl</strong> <strong>Hines</strong> just days aft=
er the <strong>R.F.K. Jr.</strong>=E2=80=93<strong>Olivia Nuzzi
</strong>story broke. But while Hines seemed committed to the bit=E2=80=94w=
earing head-to-toe Bally, including a starchy white shirt and a pair of app=
le red Mary Janes from a Bellotti collection=E2=80=94I couldn=E2=80=99t sha=
ke the feeling that these were people who preferred the Galleria over the D=
uomo. Could Reinstein ever truly appreciate Bellotti=E2=80=99s inventions?<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>After the show was over, Bellotti once again=
 received raves for his Swiss-trope interpretations, and editors begged to =
place
personal orders. Still, I thought it was telling that he referred to Bally =
as a <em>project</em> in interviews. It was also hard to imagine it lasting=
 more than another season or two, given the lack of infrastructure surround=
ing the business. Regent would pull back in the cost-cutting process, I fig=
ured, or Bellotti would be poached.=C2=A0</p></div>
